initive story of its time. For the Common Good demonstrates how two hundred years of political, economic, and social change prompted transformation among colleges and universities—including the establishment of entirely new kinds of institutions—and refashioned higher education in the United States over time in essential and often vibrant ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aU.S. History.  ahigher education, colleges and the common good, higher education policy, history of universities, ethics and academia, American higher education, universities and public service, American universities, history of education.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171261640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501712616423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501712616/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles